November 9th-13th - Wilson Technology Department & Wilson Media Productions

Tech

Number of hours this week: 16
Number of hours this semester:139

Summary

On Monday, I worked on a few Chromebooks. The first was a flip with camera issues caused by the display cable. I had another V4 with a dead mobo which I removed from service and deprovisioned (but later found out that it was still under warranty, but it was caught and corrected, but would have been bad if it wasn't). The third was a bad LCD that was first having some weird color problems along with some fractures, but when trying to replace it showed its true issue. The last chromebook was a flip that had its screen falling from its lid which is a pretty common problem with the flips because if the metal bezel becomes slightly deformed whatsoever, the screen will not stay seated. It is easily fixed by attaching a piece of adhesive. I unboxed ~15 chromebooks to clear off a cart.

On Tuesday, I worked on a chromebook that apparently wasn't turning on, but it turned on just fine for me. I then did a flip that was stuck in recovery, but just because the power button wasnt working so you couldn't have it accept the usb recovery (which is done by pressing Esc+Refresh+Power). Because of this, the motherboard is considered dead. I went to Southern with Ryan to put in a new access point there. We had to find the cable in the right network closet to attach it to the network, which we did successfully. We then ran the wire that was stowed away in the ceiling all the way across the room. The AP took forever to boot so we took it down because booting shouldn't take that long. We then looked at where Cornwall wanted to put up an AP outside and we picked up chromebooks. We went back to the office and I worked on a chromebook that had a backlight that kept going out. I reseated the cable screen-side because the latch wasn't down all the way.

On Wednesday, I did two Chromebooks: one was not turning on (dead motherboard) and the other one wasn't detecting it's webcam. I tried 2 different lids, 3 different display cables, and 2 different webcams, but still nothing worked, so we deemed it camera blind (an uncommon, but still relevant issue in the flips that they just refuse to see their camera whatever happens). Ryan helped me connect to the media server through Windows Explorer and also changed permissions so we could access it through our accounts. I went through a box of chargers and put them together.

On Thursday, Andrew had me go out and return a laptop to Mrs. Witmoyer then pick up a another computer from Mrs. Petrous. When the power button was pressed the light would go on for a few seconds, then just turn off. I took it back to the office and it powered up just fine with our cable. I took it back and even our new charger didn't work. I figured out that it was the two outlets on her wall so I recommended that she submit a ticket to operations. I went back and worked on a V3 with a touchpad that wasn't clicking right, so replaced the touchpad. I worked on a flip with no webcam and fixed it by just replacing the webcam (which was a lot easier than the day before). I then worked on the laptop that I brought up a couple weeks ago that kept blue screening (when Windows crashes while it is running, it comes up with a blue screen that gives helpful information, but in this case it blue screens on boot, so it just says "startup failed"). I tried reimaging, then reimaging on another computer and swapping over the hard drive, neither worked. Bean also gave me a laptop to test and see if the fan worked fine, which it did.

On Friday, I worked on two Chromebooks. One was a dead flip, and the other was a dead V4 (the V4 was under warranty which was nice). Operations worked on getting the lift out of the lift room. (this day was short because the filming at quest diagnostics took up most of my tech time)

Rating: 4/5

I gave myself this rating because I feel like I did a lot of good work this week and always got things done in a timely manner.

Summary

On Monday, I mainly worked on community spotlight. Later in the day there was a board meeting.

On Tuesday, I started editing the full sequence of pawsitive and slotted everything in. I got the stuff to get ready to head down to the auditorium to set up for the jazz concert. I brought up the cameras and put them in their spots but didn't set them up yet. I went into lower to set up the stream but the xps was in the studio. I went back up and finished editing the full sequence by adding in an early render of spotlight. We went down to the aud and emily started setting up mics and I made the splash. Media people arrived and we set up the cameras. I then was put in charge of audio and configured the sound board (after some help with rone) to be blank with just simple levels. I quickly set up a piano mic right before the show started because they needed one. We finished around 8:15 and cleaned up.

On Wednesday,Rone asked if we were able to record an interview for him and brandon took it. He packed stuff up and left, but later found out that the camera didn't have a working 1/8th output for monitoring audio levels so I grabbed another nx cam and the 4k as a backup and brought it over to him at cornwall. I met up with him in the library and we recorded the first bit. The next was transitions and the closing statements. Then there was a group was a group of 5th graders that read segments of 'oh the places you'll go' as a poem thing. We tore down and left. I went down to lower media and grabbed the xps. I set it up with the monitor and connected all of the cameras.

On Thursday, I mainly edited community spotlight again. I pushed through it and rone watched it and made comments. I got footage of my computer and rendered it out and put it in the full sequence. I had to make very minor changes multiple times and it took like 5 minutes to render for each. I then worked on getting the xps set up for smash. I took it over to a409 on a media cart with everything I needed and got it connected with everything.

On Friday, I went down with rone to the gym and grabbed the mics from there. We grabbed the festoons and hung them up in the aud on the second electrical. It took a while but it ended up being good. I grabbed the camera from stage tech that ava dropped off. We got the truck from gurski and brought it up.

Rating: 4/5

I gave myself this rating because I am really proud of how the community spotlight turned out, but am not proud of how long it took to get it all done.
